Creating a Stacked barplot:

# creating stacked barplot
library("tibble")
library(ggplot2)
temp = read.table( "./temp", header=TRUE, sep="\t" )
fly_data = as_tibble(temp)
fly_data
## # A tibble: 420 x 5
##    species class        copy_number     bp percent
##    <fct>   <fct>              <int>  <dbl>   <dbl>
##  1 dana    RC/Helitron           92  56127 0.0559 
##  2 dana    DNA/PiggyBac          19   6269 0.00624
##  3 dana    Unknown               17   3601 0.00359
##  4 dana    LINE/I               100 130664 0.130  
##  5 dana    LTR/Pao              254 154165 0.153  
##  6 dana    LTR/Gypsy            415 340906 0.339  
##  7 dana    LINE/CR1              37  42899 0.0427 
##  8 dana    LINE/R1               56  35027 0.0349 
##  9 dana    DNA/hAT               22   9750 0.00971
## 10 dana    DNA/hAT               35  24751 0.0246 
## #  with 410 more rows
fly_data$species = factor(fly_data$species,levels = c( "dvir", "dmoj", "dwil", "dper", "dpse", "dana", "dbip", "dbia", "dtri", "deug", "dmel", "dsec", "dsim", "dmau", "dere", "dyak" ))
p = ggplot(fly_data, aes(fill=class, y=percent, x=species)) + geom_bar( stat="identity", position="fill")
p + labs( x = "Species", y = "Percent composition of Repeat",
          title = "Percent composition of each TE class within respective Nanopore assembly" )
